<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="47" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
A genus of the julid tribe 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Verhoeff" authorityYear="1899" lsidName="" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" rank="tribe" tribe="Pachyiulini">Pachyiulini</taxonomicName>
, distinguished from all contribal genera by the unique presence of a lateral process on the opisthomere, as well as by the following combination of gonopodal and external somatic characters: promere with mesal ridge distally extending in a strong process, caudal face without apical denticles/ridges; opisthomere without anterior and caudal lamellae or these being vestigial, mesomeral process well-differentiated, crest-like, solenomere with a deep and narrow apical fovea; ommatidia absent, mandibular stipites in males not expanded, vertigial and metazonal setae present, pre-anal ring with an epiproct.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="47" type="name">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Name.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="47">
Derived from the Latin 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">bellator</emphasis>
meaning 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“soldier”">&quot;soldier&quot;</normalizedToken>
, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“warrior”">&quot;warrior&quot;</normalizedToken>
, after the remarkably 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“armed”">&quot;armed&quot;</normalizedToken>
appearance of the gonopods including the club-like mesal and lateral processes of the promere and the opisthomere, respectively, and the apically serrated mesomeral process; plus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" class="Diplopoda" family="Julidae" genus="Julus" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Julus" order="Julida" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="47">Julus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the type genus of the family 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Leach" authorityYear="1814" class="Diplopoda" family="Julidae" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="" order="Julida" pageId="0" pageNumber="47" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Julidae</taxonomicName>
. Masculine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
